<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Is it competition?<br>
If so, why not try to make it healthy competition, so when you leave, it's either &quot;damn that was fun!&quot; or &quot;damn! We'll get em next time!&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
-- Raalf quotes<br>
<br>
Because it's EQ. There may not be a &quot;next time&quot; for days on sought-after mobs. People don't get pissed off over the lost mobs so much as lost time &amp; opportunities that may not happen for you again, especially if you can't devote hours every day. Younger players tend to shrug it off when they tick someone off, older players take it seriously, or, IMO, at least reflect on how they affect others, who know that time literally = $$.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Is it personal?<br>
If so, maybe you need to look for another hobby, which involves even less human contact.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Similar to IRL, the quantity of people you meet in EQ means next to nothing compared to the quality. If you want to generalize, all of us are antisocial to some degree for choosing a virtual world over the real one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>All I ask is for a personal account of why you are so moved to be hateful to each other. Not a &quot;one time, at orc camp&quot; deal. I could care less who KSd who at Sontalak in 2001; I'm more interested in &quot;I feel like bitchslapping Ishan because:&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Well...through unrelated Wraith bashing threads that have popped up here and there, mostly at a few people that pissed a lot off (that manaburn incident, ruining someone's quest), once in a while I'd get a /tell in-game about what a mindless guild they were. I'd engage a friend, nod, and take it with a grain of salt. I kept a neutral attitude until, yep, I got pissed off too, and considered that neutral tone a wasted effort. Disappointed, in my eyes, for proving me wrong.<br>
<br>
As for your suggestion that we would all get along IRL... I doubt it. In my experience if you get the impression that someone is a pompous ass online, when you meet them in person they will remain a pompous ass. There's no substitute for looking someone in the eye, but impressions stick for a reason, even in a virtual world. So no, I'd have to say a Wraith/LC bash would not change many views. As for myself, that's even more so. Aside from age disparities and -not- finding something cool a teenager would find, I believe that if you tend to have an explanation for every behavior/attitude/and need to curb the truth for the sake of sticking up for your friends, you will tend to have an explanation for everything IRL.<br>
<br>
P.S. I miss corpse art. =/ <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=warlordette>Warlordette</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>F Salta!!!</span><br>  Posts: 247<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(10/30/02 3:12:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=624.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Lotus Cult and Wraith - please check this.</span><hr size=1> Salta...while the stuff you post could possibly be the truth, or raise a valid point.  You tend to always post things in a manner that is inflamatory, and seems to have no other purpose than to piss people off or belittle them....<br>
